--
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- 2. THREE PATTERNS FOR CHANGING A SKILL'S FUNCTION
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- [PATTERN A] Bake in a pass/fail skill as always-succeeding (Identify Item,
-- Repair Item). Only works when the skill's entire gameplay effect is a
-- single documented pass/fail event this project already installed --
-- check first (grep for "Can<X>" in Scripts/General/ExtraEvents.lua and
-- similar). Frees the slot completely, no leftover semantics to redirect:
--   function events.CanIdentifyItem(t)
--       t.CanIdentify = true
--   end
-- Before assuming a skill is this simple, grep the whole project for the
-- skill constant (const.Skills.X) to make sure there's no OTHER gameplay
-- effect hiding elsewhere (Learning looked like it might be this simple but
-- wasn't -- see Pattern C's caveat below).
--
-- [PATTERN B] Repurpose the slot for a genuinely new, independently
-- trainable skill (Cleave on Stealing, Guardian on Identify Item, Mana
-- Shield on Identify Monster, Retaliation on Learning). The full template,
-- proven four times now:
--   1. events.GameInitialized2(): Game.SkillNames[SLOT] = "New Name",
--      set Game.SkillDescriptions/SkillDesNormal/SkillDesExpert/
--      SkillDesMaster/SkillDesGM[SLOT], grant access to every class (see
--      the mastery-cap donor note below), don't bother with the "show in
--      skill screen" ASM patch Cleave.lua carries over from Stealing.lua.
--      disabled UNLESS the donor skill has the same display quirk (it's
--      Stealing-specific; every skill repurposed so far has NOT needed it).
--   2. events.PopulateLearnSkillsDialog: add SLOT to Training halls'
--      teachable list (or wherever thematically fits).
--   3. Mastery: auto-promote from raw skill level via a dedicated
--      SyncXMastery(player) function (reads/writes player.Skills[SLOT]
--      directly -- a raw memory array, confirmed independent of any
--      GetSkill hook, see 00 structs.lua's array(39).i2 'Skills' field),
--      called from events.GetSkill when t.Skill==SLOT. Thresholds
--      1/4/7/10 -> Normal/Expert/Master/GM, matching Cleave.lua's own
--      convention (used in preference to MAW's own suggested Cover/Guardian
--      thresholds of 6/12/20 -- consistency with this project's other
--      repurposed skills mattered more than matching MAW's tuning).
--      ALWAYS decode/encode the raw value with the project's own
--      SplitSkill(val) -> (level, mastery) and JoinSkill(level, mastery)
--      globals (Scripts/Structs/After/Functions.lua) -- do NOT hand-roll
--      bit.band/bit.lshift on a made-up MASTERY_MASK. See gotcha #1 below;
--      this exact template:
--        local function SyncXMastery(player)
--            local stored = player.Skills[SLOT]
--            if not stored or stored == 0 then return nil, 0 end
--            local level, curMastery = SplitSkill(stored)
--            if level < 1 then return nil, 0 end
--            local expected = MasteryFromLevel(level)
--            -- (class cap check here)
--            if curMastery ~= expected then
--                player.Skills[SLOT] = JoinSkill(level, expected)
--            end
--            return expected, level
--        end
--        function events.GetSkill(t)
--            if t.Player and t.Skill == SLOT then
--                local mastery = SyncXMastery(t.Player)
--                if mastery then
--                    local lvl, curMas = SplitSkill(t.Result)
--                    if mastery > curMas then t.Result = JoinSkill(lvl, mastery) end
--                end
--            end
--        end
--   4. Per-class mastery caps: do NOT just grant "Normal to everyone with
--      zero access" and stop there -- the slot inherits the DONOR skill's
--      original per-class distribution, which is often thematically wrong
--      for the new skill (confirmed bug: Knight capped at Normal for
--      Guardian because Identify Item's own class table gives Knights zero
--      access; Identify Item is a scholarly/merchant skill, Knights aren't
--      rated on it). Instead mirror a DIFFERENT, thematically-fitting
--      existing skill's per-class caps wholesale:
--          skills[SLOT] = math.max(skills[const.Skills.DonorSkill], 1)
--      (the math.max floor of 1 keeps it learnable by every class even if
--      the donor skill has zero access for some of them). Donors used so
--      far: Guardian -> Shield (defensive), Mana Shield -> Meditation
--      (mana-management), Retaliation -> Armsmaster (melee prowess).
--      Pick whatever's thematically closest for the next one.
--   5. The actual mechanic: write it for THIS project's own damage/stat
--      formulas, don't try to port MAW's version wholesale unless it's
--      genuinely self-contained (Guardian's redirect mechanic was; Mana
--      Shield's and Retaliation's damage formulas were NOT, since MAW's
--      versions depend on calcPowerVitality() and their full
--      CalcDamageToPlayer rewrite, neither of which exist here -- see
--      StatRemix.lua's header for the same situation with the Luck floor
--      and spell damage).
--
-- [PATTERN C] Merge/redirect one skill into another's value (Identify
-- Monster -> best spell school, Disarm Traps -> Perception). Use when a
-- skill's native effect should survive but doesn't need its own dedicated
-- training/slot:
--   function events.GetSkill(t)
--       if t.Skill ~= const.Skills.OldSkill or not t.Player then return end
--       t.Result = t.Player.Skills[const.Skills.NewSourceSkill]
--       -- or a derived value, e.g. ManaShield.lua's "highest of 7 schools"
--   end
-- CRITICAL CAVEAT, discovered via a real back-and-forth this session:
-- Pattern C and Pattern B CANNOT coexist on the same slot. events.GetSkill
-- has no way to distinguish "native code asking about the OLD skill's
-- native effect" from "training UI/character sheet asking about a NEW
-- skill now occupying that slot" -- both arrive as the same t.Skill==SLOT
-- with no other context. Applying Pattern C's redirect unconditionally
-- would make a Pattern-B skill on the same slot display/train using the
-- WRONG value. If a slot needs Pattern C's redirect, leave it otherwise
-- free (Pattern C alone, no new trainable skill on it) -- this is why
-- Disarm Traps (31) and, before Mana Shield claimed it, would-be conflicts
-- on Identify Monster (34) are handled as pure redirects with the slot's
-- OWN raw storage repurposed separately for the new skill's mastery
-- tracking (works because raw player.Skills[N] reads bypass GetSkill
-- entirely -- only the native function-call path native UI/training uses
-- goes through the hook). This means a Pattern-B skill built on top of a
-- Pattern-C-redirected slot (as Mana Shield is, on Identify Monster) has
-- an UNVERIFIED risk: the character sheet's own display of "Mana Shield"
-- and the training-hall's "cost to train further" calculation likely also
-- go through the same hooked GetSkill function as native Identify-Monster
-- checks do, and would show the spell-school-derived number instead of
-- Mana Shield's real trained level. Not a crash -- the actual mechanic
-- (ManaShield.lua's CalcDamageToPlayer hook) reads raw storage directly
-- and is unaffected -- but worth checking live before assuming it's fine.
-- If it IS confusing in practice, narrow the override (e.g. only apply the
-- spell-school substitution when the slot's own raw level is still 0)
-- rather than re-architecting.
--
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- 3. GOTCHAS FOUND THIS SESSION, WORTH NOT REPEATING
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- - MOST IMPORTANT, found during a later double-check pass: the raw skill
--   value is NOT a clean bitfield with mastery living at some fixed bit
--   offset. It's LEVEL + an ADDITIVE MASTERY OFFSET (Expert +0x40,
--   Master +0x80, GM +0x100 on mm8), decoded by magnitude comparison, not
--   by masking a bit range. This project already provides the correct
--   codec as globals: SplitSkill(val) -> (level, mastery 0-4) and
--   JoinSkill(level, mastery) -> val (both in
--   Scripts/Structs/After/Functions.lua, used correctly all over the rest
--   of the codebase -- RacialSkills.lua, ExtraArtifacts.lua,
--   GlobalEventsNewHandler.lua). Cleave.lua, Guardian.lua, ManaShield.lua,
--   Retaliation.lua, and SkillHarmony.lua were ALL originally written with
--   a hand-rolled scheme instead (MASTERY_MASK = 0x3C00, mastery packed at
--   bit 10 via bit.lshift(mastery-1, 10)) -- a constant that, when
--   grepped, appeared nowhere else in the entire project, which is what
--   gave the bug away. Consequence: since 0x400/0x800/0xC00 (the values
--   this scheme wrote for Expert/Master/GM) are all >= 0x100, SplitSkill
--   would decode ALL THREE as mastery 4 (GM) the instant a character's
--   skill level crossed the Expert threshold (level 4) -- Expert and
--   Master mastery were functionally unreachable; every one of these
--   skills jumped straight to full GM behavior at level 4. Worse,
--   SkillHarmony.lua applies the same write to every skill in the game
--   (0-38, not just the repurposed ones) and is on by default, so this
--   was a game-wide bug, not confined to the four new skills. Fixed by
--   replacing all of it with SplitSkill/JoinSkill (see Pattern B's
--   template above, now corrected). Skill LEVEL was never affected by
--   this bug (bit.band(stored,0x3F) and SplitSkill's val%0x40 happen to
--   agree on level extraction since the wrong offsets were multiples of
--   64) -- only mastery tier was wrong, which is why it wasn't obvious
--   from a quick smoke test at low character levels.
--
-- - GetSkill hooks must be gated behind their own Game.XEnabled toggle for
--   their ENTIRE body, not just part of it. Found and fixed a bug in
--   ManaShield.lua where the mastery-sync call was gated but the
--   spell-school override to t.Result wasn't -- meaning disabling the
--   feature didn't actually disable the Identify-Monster-via-magic-school
--   behavior. Check the whole function is behind the toggle, not just the
--   part that "does the interesting work".
--
-- - player:GetXTotalSkill() methods (GetLearningTotalSkill,
--   GetPerceptionTotalSkill, GetMerchantTotalSkill, GetDisarmTrapTotalSkill
--   -- all defined via SimplePlayerHook in Scripts/Core/events.lua) return
--   a plain bonus-inclusive aggregate number, NOT the packed level+mastery
--   format that events.GetSkill's t.Result and player.Skills[N] use
--   (decode/encode with SplitSkill/JoinSkill, see gotcha #1 above -- it's
--   an additive offset, not a bitfield). Do not substitute one for the other in a
--   Pattern C redirect -- confirmed this before it became a live bug by
--   checking the documented t.Result format against these methods'
--   naming convention (no usage example existed in this project to check
--   directly, but the format mismatch was clear enough not to risk it).
--
-- - A skill can look Pattern-A-simple (single pass/fail hook) and not be --
--   Learning looked like it might reduce to one CanX-style check, but
--   Scripts/General/Learning.lua turned out to directly patch native
--   training-time assembly (reading player.Skills[Learning] inline via
--   SplitSkill in two places) AND had a second, separate XP-boost ASM
--   patch. Always grep the whole project for the skill constant before
--   assuming Pattern A applies; Learning ended up needing its own
--   dedicated normalization (hardcode the training-time formula to always
--   use GM-equivalent mastery, drop the XP-boost patch entirely) rather
--   than a simple bake-in.
--
-- - Before repurposing ANY slot, grep Data/Tables/*.txt (Race Skills.txt,
--   Class Skills.txt, Class Starting Skills.txt, ItemsExtra.txt/
--   ExtraArtifacts.lua for item bonuses) for the skill constant. Race/
--   class tables can have auto-grant entries (Human's Learning bonus) that
--   silently carry over as "auto-grant of the NEW skill" if not caught;
--   item bonuses targeting the old skill (several +Disarm Traps artifacts
--   found in ExtraArtifacts.lua) just go inert once redirected/repurposed
--   -- not a bug, but worth knowing they're there rather than being
--   surprised later.
--
-- - Don't blindly carry over a donor skill's ASM display patch. Cleave.lua
--   carries a "show <skill> in character skills screen" ASM patch from the
--   original (disabled) Scripts/General/Stealing.lua.disabled, hardcoded
--   to compare against Stealing's own skill ID (0x24). Reading that
--   original file's comment confirmed it fixes a Stealing-specific display
--   quirk, not a generic requirement -- Guardian/Mana Shield/Retaliation
--   all skip it and (as far as tested) display fine without it. If a
--   future repurposed skill doesn't show up correctly in the skill list,
--   THAT'S the mechanism to look at, not something to preemptively copy in.
--
-- - When renaming an already-shipped repurposed skill (Cover -> Guardian),
--   grep the WHOLE project for the old name, not just the skill's own file
--   -- other skills that reference it (Retaliation.lua reads Guardian.lua's
--   vars.justGuarded marker), both reference docs, and the user-facing
--   changelog/README all need the same rename. A skill name isn't
--   self-contained to its own file once other systems hook into its
--   side-effects.
--
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- 4. THE SKILLZ.DLL DETOUR (why Pattern B exists instead of new skill slots)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Guardian (then named Cover) was originally attempted as a genuinely new
-- skill slot (beyond the vanilla hardcoded count) using
-- Malekitsu/Maw-Mod-MMMerge's Skillz.dll -- MAW's own way of doing this, a
-- compiled binary with no public source, wrapped by a thin Lua layer
-- (Scripts/Structs/00Skillz.lua in MAW's repo). After copying the DLL in
-- and fixing every missing-dependency error it surfaced (a missing
-- Data/Tables/Race Skillz.txt, a missing cave_api.dll, both copied from
-- MAW's repo), it still crashed unrecoverably -- silently, no error
-- message, nothing in either MMMergeLog.txt or MMExtensionLog.txt --
-- specifically when actually training a skill through it. This is exactly
-- the risk that was flagged before attempting it (an unverifiable compiled
-- binary, no source to debug against, no way to confirm it matches this
-- project's exact build) materializing in practice. Fully reverted (DLL,
-- wrapper module, the added data table all removed) in favor of Pattern B
-- above, which achieves the same "new trainable skill" outcome using only
-- proven, already-present Lua-level hooks. See Guardian.lua's own header
-- for the blow-by-blow.
--
-- Lesson: repurposing an EXISTING vanilla skill slot is far lower risk than
-- trying to add genuinely new ones. This project apparently has 15 "Misc"
-- category skills (24-38, see the table in section 1) as a deep pool of
-- slots to repurpose before genuinely running out.
--
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- 5. TAUNT BAKE-IN (Guardian, follow-up session)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- A separate "Taunt" skill was considered (drawing monster aggro onto a
-- character, the inverse of Guardian's reactive intercept) but rejected in
-- favor of folding a lightweight version into Guardian itself, rather than
-- spending a 5th skill slot on a mechanic that's thematically a subset of
-- what Guardian already does. Implementation: landing a melee hit grants a
-- mastery-scaled bonus (Normal +5%, Expert +10%, Master +15%, GM +20%,
-- see TAUNT_BONUS_BY_MASTERY in Guardian.lua) to that character's next
-- intercept roll -- this generalizes what used to be a GM-only +15% one-
-- shot bonus into a per-tier mechanic active at every mastery level, reused
-- from the exact same CalcDamageToMonster/PlayerAttacked hooks Guardian
-- already had, no new native hook needed.
--
-- This is explicitly the "reactive odds bump" version of Taunt, not a real
-- pre-emptive one -- it doesn't change which party member a monster picks
-- as its FIRST target, only Guardian's own chance to intercept afterward.
-- A "real" Taunt (biasing initial monster target selection) would need a
-- new, currently-undiscovered native hook into monster AI targeting --
-- worth a future investigation pass if the baked-in version doesn't feel
-- assertive enough in practice, but deliberately not attempted yet since
-- it's unproven territory (same category of risk as the abandoned
-- Skillz.dll attempt, just a different subsystem).
